Content:
Unless the subject or context otherwise requires, in this Act,
(1) 'Appellate Authority' means the appellate authority designated by
rules for the purposes of this Act;
(2) 'crops' means all types of crops, straw, grain seeds and any other
crop residues produced on land which have economic value;
(3) 'Collector' means the Collector as defined in clause (3) of section 2 of
the State Acquisition and Tenancy Act, 1950 (Act No. XXVIII of 1951),
(4) 'Khas land' means khas land as defined in clause (15) of section 2 of
the State Acquisition and Tenancy Act, 1950 (Act No. XXVIII of 1951),
and includes khas land not owned by any person, organization or other
government department and under the control of the Ministry of Lands
and the following types of land shall also be included, namely:
(a) All lands included in the Collector's Khatian No. 1 or Register No. 8;
(b) The land of a char rising from a river or the seabed, whether it is the
backwater of a siksti land or a new char;
(c) Land in excess of 1 (one) hundred bighas owned by a family or
organization, surrendered or surrenderable to the Government under
section 3 of the Bangladesh Land Holding (Limitation) Order, 1972
(President's Order No. 98 of 1972);
(d) Land purchased by the Government at auction;
(e) Land without title and claim under section 92 of the State Acquisition
and Tenancy Act, 1950 (Act No. XXVIII of 1951);
(f) the extent of land acquired for government departments or statutory
bodies which has been reacquired by the government due to its unusable
nature; and
(g) Land surrendered or surrenderable to the Government under section
4;
(5) 'Prescribed' means prescribed by rules;
(6) 'Designated Authority' means the authority designated by rules for
the purpose of this Act;
(7) 'Family' means a person and his wife, son, unmarried daughter,
daughter-in-law, grandson and unmarried granddaughter:
Provided that such adult or married son and his wife, son and unmarried
daughter, who are living independently of their parents and paying Union
Holding Tax in their own name, shall be considered as a separate family;
(8) 'Rural area' means all areas not included in the areas designated by a
city corporation, municipality, industrial zone or special zone declared by
the government or any special organization declared by the government;
(9) 'standard bigha' means 33 (thirty-three) hundredths of a bigha;
(10) 'Criminal Procedure Code' means the Code of Criminal Procedure,
1898 (Act No. V of 1898);
(11) 'Bargadar' means a person who cultivates the land of another
person in the customary manner as adhi, barga or bhag cultivator on
condition that he surrenders a part of the produce of the said land to that
person;
(12) 'shareholder agreement' means an agreement under which a person
cultivates any land as a sharer;
(13) 'Barga land' means any land under cultivation by a person as a
tenant farmer;
(14) 'homestead' means homestead as defined in clause (14) of section
2 of the State Acquisition and Tenancy Act, 1950 (Act No. XXVIII of
1951);
(15) 'Personal cultivation' means cultivation by any person
(a) by his own labor, or
(b) by the labour of any member of his family, or
(c) Cultivation of one's own land or sharecropping by the labour of
oneself or any member of one's family or by the labour of a wage-earning
worker;
(16) 'Rules' means rules made under this Act;
(17) 'land' means land as defined in clause (16) of section 2 of the State
Acquisition and Tenancy Act, 1950 (Act No. XXVIII of 1951);
(18) 'Land Reforms Board' means the Land Reforms Board as defined in
section 2 of the Land Reforms Board Act, 1989 (Act No. 23 of 1989);
(19) 'Land Office' means the Collector and the offices under the Collector
which conduct all land related activities;
(20) 'Owner of land' means any person from whom the tenant has
acquired land for cultivation under a tenancy agreement;
(21) 'Owner' means any person, company, organization, institution or
authority in possession of agricultural land; and
(22) 'Institution' means any body or company, firm, society, association,
organization or authority by whatever name it may be called, recognized
by the Government.
